Using the Granger causality F-test in a pair-wise way, we can check whether the null hypothesis, stating that one series {
 X

  t
 } does not affect the other one {
 Y

  t
 }, can be rejected or not. If the hypothesis is rejected, then the time-series {
 X

  t
 } affects the series {
 Y

  t
 }. Thus, from a rather heuristic point of view, this indicates that past values of {
 X

  t
 } can be used for the prediction of future values of {
 Y

  t
 }. Otherwise stated, the values used for describing the autoregressive equation for {
 Y

  t
 } have significant non-zero contribution of past values of {
 X

  t
 }. The model including {
 X

  t
 } is called unrestricted model, in opposition to the restricted case where the series {
 X

  t
 } is not included in the analysis, see [
 11].
